ol]], [[Gloucestershire]] for [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]], [[British North America]]. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=Times230363>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=23 March 1863 |page_number=11 |issue=24513 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Drontheim''\n|flag={{flag|Norway|1844}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was driven ashore and wrecked in Loch Tarbert. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=Times081162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Free Trade''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. Her crew were resued by the [[full-rigged ship]] ''Montebello'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Free Trade'' was on a voyage from [[London]] to [[New York City|New York]], United States.<ref name=Times111162>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=11 November 1862 |page_number=10 |issue=24400 |column=D }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jessie'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brigantine]] foundered in the [[North Sea]] {{convert|120|nmi|km}} north east of [[Peterhead]], [[Aberdeenshire]]. Her crew were rescued by a Dutch [[fishing smack]]. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Aberdeen]].<ref name=S081162>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=8 November 1862 |issue=11932 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Treumais'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship collided with a British [[steamship]] and sank off [[Padstow]], [[Cornwall]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] with the loss of two of her six crew. She was on a voyage from [[Swansea]], [[Glamorgan]] to [[La Rochelle]], [[Charente-Inf\u00e9rieure]].<ref name=S031162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Windrush'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] foundered in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] off [[Oliva]], Spain with the loss of four of her five crew. The survivor was rescued by ''San Antonio'' ({{flag|Spain|civil-1785}}).<ref name=LG221162>{{Cite news |title=General Intelligence |newspaper=Lancaster Gazetteer |location=Lancaster |date=22 November 1862 |issue=3947 |page=2 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Zitto'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was in collision with a [[barque]] and was then run ashore {{convert|12|nmi|km}} east of [[Almer\u00eda]], Spain. She was on a voyage from [[Messina]], [[Sicily]] to London.<ref name=LM011162/><ref name=S011162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==31 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=31 October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Bergman''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The ship departed from [[New York City|New York]] for [[London]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=Times160263>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=16 February 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24483 |column=E }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Grace Evans'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was run into by the [[frigate]] {{ship|Egyptian frigate|Feyz-i Cihat||2}}<!--incorrectly named by source--> ({{flagicon|Ottoman Empire|naval-1844}} [[Egyptian Navy]]) in the [[River Mersey]] and was severely damaged. She was towed in to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]].<ref name=LM031162>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=3 November 1862 |issue=4596 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rosina'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore. She was on a voyage from [[G\u00e4vle]], Sweden to London.<ref name=LM011162/> She was refloated on 4 November and taken in to Baltic Port.<ref name=S141162>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=14 November 1862 |issue=11937 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Seabor Brother'' \n|flag={{flag|Hamburg|admiralty}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the [[North Sea]] {{convert|75|nmi|km}} off [[Heligoland]]. Her eight crew were rescued by the [[schooner]] ''Peter and Jane'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=NC071162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==Unknown date==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=Unknown date in October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Albertina'' \n|flag={{flag|Belgium}}\n|desc=The ship was lost either on the Fahludd Reef, in the [[Baltic Sea]], or on [[Fehmarn]], [[Duchy of Holstein]]. She was on a voyage from [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to [[Antwerp]].<ref name=LM081062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Alderman Thompson'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was wrecked at [[Cardigan, Ceredigion|Cardigan]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]], to Cardigan.<ref name=Cardigan>{{cite web |url=http://www.glen-johnson.co.uk/cardigan-district-shipwrecks-and-lifeboat-service/ |title=Cardigan & District Shipwrecks and Lifeboat Service |publisher=Glen Johnson |accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Alleghanian''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: Bound from [[Baltimore, Maryland]], to [[London]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]], with a cargo of [[guano]], the 1,120 or 1,400-ton [[full-rigged ship]] was boarded and set afire sometime between 28 and 30 October by the crews of three [[Confederate States Navy]] small boats while at anchor in the [[Chesapeake Bay]] near [[Gwynn's Island]], {{convert|5|to|12|mi|km}} off the mouth of [[Virginia]]\u2032s [[Rappahannock River]]. After the Confederates fled, {{USS|T. A. Wood}} and the [[gunboat]] {{USS|Crusader|1858|6}} (both {{navy|United States|1861}}) extinguished the flames, but the Confederates returned and set another fire that destroyed the ship.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref name=gainesp175>Gaines, p. 175.</ref><ref name=S131162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Alma'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was driven ashore on Oyster Island, [[County Sligo]].<ref name=S301062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ann and Elizabeth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned before 28 October. She was on a voyage from Iceland to [[Barcelona]], Spain.<ref name=S311062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ann and Isabella''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked at the mouth of the Chischa River, Russia before 11 October. Her crew survived.<ref name=Times241062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''A. Smithers''\n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[British North America]]\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was abandoned off [[Bermuda]] with the loss of two of her seven crew. Survivors were rescued by ''Pfeil'' ({{flag|Bremen}}). ''A. Smithers'' was on a vogage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to [[Santiago de Cuba]], [[Captaincy General of Cuba|Cuba]].<ref name=Times011162>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=1 November 1862 |page_number=12 |issue=24392 |column=C }}</ref><ref name=S011162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Blue Rock'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the [[Pacific Ocean]] {{convert|200|nmi|km}} south west of[[Iquique]], Chile. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=BDP301062>{{Cite news |title=The West India Mail |newspaper=Birmingham Daily Post |location=Birmingham |date=30 October 1862 |issue=1330 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Braes o{{'}}Murray'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was discovered derelict off the [[Farne Islands]], [[Northumberland]].<ref name=NC160163>{{Cite news |title=Marine Intelligence |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=16 January 1863 |issue=9812 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship||Cadboro|1824 schooner|2}}\n|flag=Flag unknown\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was lost near [[Port Angeles, Washington|Port Angeles]], [[Washington Territory]].<ref name=gainesp194>Gaines, p. 194.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Cincinnatus'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=The [[full-rigged ship]] was destroyed by fire in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] before 3 October. She was on a voyage from [[Newport, Monmouthshire]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] to [[Shanghai]], [[Qing dynasty|China]].<ref name=S061062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Comet'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=American Civil War: The [[schooner]] was destroyed by {{USS|Dacotah}} ({{navy|United States|1861}}). She was on a voyage from [[Matanzas]] to [[Havana]], Cuba.<ref name=S011162>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=1 November 1862 |issue=11926 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Commerce''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The[[collier (ship type)|collier]], a [[brig]], foundered in the North Sea {{convert|30|nmi|km}} off [[Spurn Point]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]]. Her crew were rescued by a fishing [[lugger]].<ref name=Times281062>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Collier Vessels, Shields, Oct. 26 |date=28 October 1862 |page_number=9 |issue=24388 |column=D }}</ref><ref name=NC311062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Conchita''\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War, [[Union blockade]]: The [[schooner]] was captured and burned off the coast of [[Louisiana]] or [[Texas]] near [[Calcasieu Pass]] and [[Sabine Pass]].<ref>Gaines, pp. 167-168.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Cybele'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked near \"Marberg\". She was on a voyage fro