own, County Cork]].<ref name=Times271062/><ref name=S271062b/><ref name=ES311062>{{Cite news |title=The Late Terrific Gales at Sea |newspaper=Essex Standard |location=Colchester |date=31 October 1862 |issue=1663 |page=1 |volume=32 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Tom Cochrane''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1860}}\n|desc=The 14-ton [[screw steamer]] was stranded at [[Sturgeon Point Light|Sturgeon Point]] on the [[Lake Huron]] coast of Michigan.<ref name=gainesp81/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Whim''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the North Sea. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Hamburg]] to [[Hartlepool]], County Durham.<ref name=Times011162/><ref name=NC071162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''William Henry''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was run into by the [[full-rigged ship]] ''Reliance'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and was abandoned. Her crew were rescued by ''Reliance''. ''William Henry'' was on a voyage from [[Boston, Massachusetts]], United States to Liverpool.<ref name=Times231062a/><ref name=SI221062/> She had come ashore near [[Blackpool]], Lancashire by 22 October.<ref name=Times241062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Yarmouth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked near [[Varberg]], Sweden.<ref name=LM171062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* [http://scubagonewild.com/documents/Encyclopedia%20of%20Civil%20War%20Shipwrecks%20-%20(Malestrom).pdf Gaines, W. Craig, ''Encyclopedia of Civil War Shipwrecks'', Louisiana State University Press, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-8071-3274-6}}.]\n\n{{shipevents|1862}}\n{{1860s shipwrecks}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of shipwrecks by year|1862-10]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in October 1862]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks in October 1862''' includes [[ship]]s sunk, foundered, grounded, or otherwise lost during October [[1862]].\n{{Calendar ToC}}\n\n==1 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=1 October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Barbara and Margaret''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on \"Hastend Island\". Her crew were rescued.<ref name=Times081162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Elizabeth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore at [[Redcar]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]].<ref name=LM031062>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=3 October 1862 |issue=4570 }}</ref><ref name=S031062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=3 October 1862 |issue=11901 |page=7 }}</ref> She was on a voyage from [[Wisbech]], [[Cambridgeshire]] to [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]]. She was refloated the next day and taken in to [[Hartlepool]], [[County Durham]] for repairs.<ref name=S041062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=4 October 1862 |issue=11902 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ida'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was driven ashore in the [[Bosphorus]] opposite [[Therapia]], [[Ottoman Empire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Odessa]] to [[Smyrna]], Ottoman Empire and [[London]].<ref name=S111062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Marice'' \n|flag={{flag|Hamburg|admiralty}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was lost off \"Wardoe\". Her crew were rescued.<ref name=S131162>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=13 November 1862 |issue=11936 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''South Sea'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked at the Sand Heads, [[british Raj|India]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Calcutta]], India to London.<ref name=DN281062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 October 1862|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{PS|Iona|1855|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: The 325-[[gross ton]] sidewheel [[paddle steamer]], a [[Blockade runners of the American Civil War|blockade runner]], collided with the [[steamship]] {{SS|Chanticleer|1862|2}} ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and sank in the [[Firth of Clyde]].<ref name=gainesp37>Gaines, p. 37.</ref><ref name=GH031062>{{Cite news |title=Loss of the Iona |newspaper=Glasgow Herald |location=Glasgow |date=3 October 1862 |issue=7092 |edition=Afternoon }}</ref> Her crew survived.<ref name=S041062/> She was on a voyage from [[Glasgow]], [[Renfrewshire]] to [[Nassau, Bahamas]].<ref name=S111062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=11 October 1862 |issue=11908 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sandelma'' \n|flag={{flag|Denmark}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the Paternoster Rocks, in the [[Baltic Sea]]. She was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] to [[Copenhagen]].<ref name=S061062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''William Ingles'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Shipwash Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Suffolk]] and was abandoned by her crew. She was on a voyage from [[Sines]], Portugal to [[London]]. She had become a wreck by the next day.<ref name=Benham>{{cite book |title=The Salvagers |first=Hervey |last=Benham |authorlink=Hervey Benham |pages=188-89 |publisher=Essex County Newspapers Ltd |location=Colchester |year=1980 |isbn=00 950944 2 3}}</ref><ref name=S061062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=6 October 1862 |issue=11903 |page=7 }}</ref><ref name=ES101062>{{Cite news |title=Harwich |newspaper=Essex Standard |location=Colchester |date=10 October 1862 |issue=1660 |volume=39 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Young Elizabeth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked at [[Aberystwyth]], [[Cardiganshire]].<ref name=LM031062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=3 October 1862|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Annie Gibson'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore at [[Bamburgh]], [[Northumberland]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from the [[River Clyde|Clyde]] to [[Dunkerque]], [[Nord (departements)|Nord]], France.<ref name=S041062/> She was refloated and taken in to [[Berwick upon Tweed]], [[Northumberland]].<ref name=S071062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Antigua'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground in [[Lake Saint Pierre]]. She was on a voyage from [[Montreal]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]] to the [[river Clyde|Clyde]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=LM171062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Brilliant''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[CSS Alabama's New England Expeditionary Raid|CSS ''Alabama''{{'}}s New England Expeditionary Raid]]: The 839-ton ship, carrying a cargo of [[flour]] and [[grain]] from [[New York City|New York]] to [[London]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] was captured and burned on the [[Grand Banks of Newfoundland]] near {{coord|40|00|N|50|30|W|name=''Brilliant''}} by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America}}).<ref name=macslogalabama>[http://ahoy.tk-jk.net/MaraudersCivilWar/CSSAlabama.html Ahoy - Mac's Web Log \"Marauders of the Sea, Confederate Merchant Raiders During the American Civil War: CSS Alabama. 1862-1864. Captain Raphael Semmes\"]</ref><ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862>[http://www.usnlp.org/navychronology/1862b.html usnlp.org Navy Chronology of the Civil War, July-December 1862]</ref><ref name=gainesp32>Gaines, p. 32.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''David Begg'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the [[Indian Ocean]]. Her crew were rescued by the [[barque]] ''Countess of Yarborough'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''David Begg'' was on a voyage from [[Calcutta]], [[British Raj|India]] to Liverpool. Her crew alleged that her captain [[barratry (admiralty law)|deliberately scuttled the vessel]].<ref name=MP281162>{{Cite news |title=The Cape of Good Hope |newspaper=Morning Post |location=London |date=28 November 1862 |issue=27752 |page=5 }}</ref><ref name=GH011262>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Glasgow Herald |location=Glasgow |date=1 December 1862 |issue=7142 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''James'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the Gunfleet Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage to [[London]].<ref name=S071062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=7 October 1862 |issue=11904 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jane and Elizabeth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] ran aground on the Vlie Banks, off the coast of [[Friesland]], Netherlands. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Hamburg]]. She was a total loss.<ref name=S071062/><ref name=LM081062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship collided with ''Ada'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and sank in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Norfolk]]. Her crew were rescued by ''Ada''. ''Mary'' was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Le Tr\u00e9port]], [[Seine-Inf\u00e9rieure]], France.<ref name=Times071062>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=7 October 1862 |page_number=12 |issue=24370 |column=C }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary and Alice'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Portpatrick]], [[Wigtownshire]].<ref name=S041062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Nepaul'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned at sea. Her crew were rescued by ''Brothers'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Nepaul'' was on a voyage from [[Kurrachee]], [[British Raj|India]] to [[Falmouth, Cornwall]].<ref name=LM291162a/><ref name=S291162>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=29 November 1862 |issue=11950 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Spy'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore. She was on a voyage from [[Demerara]], [[British Guiana]] to [[London]]. She was refloated and assisted in to [[Dover]], [[Kent]].<ref name=S071062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unnamed\n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the [[Kentish Knock (England)|Kentish Knock]]. She was refloated.<ref name=S071062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ann Augusta'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground in the [[Belfast Lough]]. She was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to [[Belfast]], [[County Antrim]].<ref name=S071062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Aspasia'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship struck a sunken rock and was run ashore at \"Takli\", [[Russian Empire|Russia]], where she was wrecked. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Taganrog]], Russia to a British port.<ref name=S071062/><ref name=S221062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Johan Morhr'' \n|flag={{flag|Prussia|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore on \"Leskr\", Russia. She was on a voyage from Cronstadt to [[Lubawka|Liebau]]. She was refloated and put back to Cronstadt.<ref name=S131062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] collided with the [[barque]] ''Ada'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and sank in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Norfolk]]. Her crew were rescued by ''Ada''. ''Mary'' was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Le Tr\u00e9port]], [[Seine-Inf\u00e9rieure]], France.<ref name=S071062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary Gillespie'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the Cross Sand, in the North Sea off the coast of Norfolk. She was on a voyage from [[Blyth, Northumberland]] to [[boulogne-sur-Mer|Boulogne]], [[Pas-de-Calais]], France. She was refloated and taken in to [[Great Yarmouth]], Norfolk.<ref name=S071062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Oscar''\n|flag={{flag|Sweden|1844}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked on [[\u00d6land]]. She was on a voyage from [[Ystad]] to [[London]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]].<ref name=Times231062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pacha'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on Morups Reef, in the [[Baltic Sea]]. She was on a voyage from [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]] to [[Cronstadt]], Russia.<ref name=S071062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==5 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=5 October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Carl Stemorth'' \n|flag={{flag|Prussia|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was driven ashore {{convert|3|nmi|km}} west of [[Roquetas]], Spain. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Odessa]] to [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]].<ref name=S071062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Dykes''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was wrecked on [[Anticosti Island]], [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]]. Her crew survived. She was on a voyage from [[Maryport]], [[Cumberland]] to [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], British North America.<ref name=Times251162>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=25 November 1862 |page_number=12 |issue=24412 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=LM141162>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=14 November 1862 |issue=4606 }}</ref><ref name=GH241162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Magari Gezina''\n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the Spikeway, in the [[North Sea]]. She was on a voyage from [[Groningen (city)|Groningen]] to [[London]], United Kingdom.<ref name=Times121262>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=12 December 1862 |page_number=9 |issue=24427 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Tubal Cain'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] ran aground on the [[Scroby Sands]], [[Norfolk]]. She was on a voyage from [[Blyth, Northumberland]] to [[Deal, Kent]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=S071062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Arthur Childs'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship departed from [[New York City|New York]], United States for the [[River Clyde|Clyde]]. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=LM190163>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=16 January 1863 |issue=4662 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jane and Isabella'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] ran aground south west of [[Island of Stroma|Stroma]], [[Orkney Islands]]. She was on a voyage from [[Fraserburgh]], [[Aberdeenshire]] to [[Belfast]], [[County Antrim]]. She was refloated.<ref name=AJ081062a>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Aberdeen Journal |location=Aberdeen |date=8 October 1862 |issue=5987 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mauritius''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the Atlantic Ocean. All on board were rescued. She was discovered on 7 October by the [[barque]] ''Orixa'' ({{flag|France}}) and ''Shakespeare'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). Five crew from ''Orixa'' and four from ''Shakespear'' were put aboard ''Maritius'' with the intention of taking her in to [[Saint Helena]], but she subsequently foundered. Only one crew member originally from ''Orixa'' was rescued.<ref name=Times011262>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=1 December 1862 |page_number=12 |issue=24417 |column=F }}</ref> ''Mauritius'' was on a voyage from [[Greenock]], [[Renfrewshire]] to [[Kurrachee]], [[British Raj|India]].<ref name=MP281162>{{Cite news |title=The Cape of Good Hope |newspaper=Morning Post |location=London |date=28 November 1862 |issue=27752 |page=5 }}</ref><ref name=LM291162a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Spring'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Sheringham Shoal, in the [[North Sea]] of the coast of [[Norfolk]]. She was on a voyage from [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]] to [[London]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage, but consequently sank {{convert|6|nmi|km}} off the coast. her crew were rescued.<ref name=S091062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Walker Lass'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Redcar]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]].<ref name=S161062/> She was on a voyage from [[Skinningrove]], Yorkshire to South Shields.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unnamed\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] foundered in the [[North Sea]] {{convert|20|nmi|km}} off the coast of Aberdeenshire. Her three crew took to a boat; they were rescued by the [[tugboat|tug]] ''Britannia'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=AJ081062>{{Cite news |title=(letter) |author=Amor \u00c6quitatus |newspaper=Aberdeen Journal |location=Abredeen |date=8 October 1862 |issue=5987 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==7 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=7 October 1862|sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''David and John'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore at [[Gosforth]], [[Northumberland]]. She was on a voyage from [[Montrose, Forfarshire]] to [[Seaham]], [[County Durham]].<ref name=S091062/> She was refloated the next day and towed in to [[Berwick upon Tweed]], Northumberland.<ref name=S101062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=10 October 1862 |issue=11907 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Dunkirk''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1861}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[CSS Alabama's New England Expeditionary Raid|CSS ''Alabama''{{'}}s New England Expeditionary Raid]]: During a voyage from [[New York City|New York]] to [[Lisbon]], Portugal, with a cargo of [[flour]] and [[Portuguese language]] [[bible]]s, the 293-ton [[brig]] was captured and burned in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] southeast of [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]] by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America}}).<ref name=macslogalabama/><ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref name=gainesp32/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Elizabeth''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[collier (ship type)|collier]], a [[brig]], was run down and sunk in the [[North Sea]] off the ''[[Sunk Lightship]]'' ([[File:Trinity House Ensign (pre-1937).svg|22px]] [[Trinity House]]) by a [[steamship]] with the loss of five of her crew.<ref name=Times131062>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=13 October 1862 |page_number=10 |issue=24375 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Forrester''<!--{{PS|Forrester|1848|2}}?-->, and<br>{{PS|Tynemouth|1862|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] ''Forrester'' was run into by the [[paddle steamer]] ''Tynemouth'' and sank in the [[River Tyne]] with the loss of six lives. She was on a voyage from [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]] to [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]]. ''Tynemouth'' was on a voyage from South Shields to Newcastle upon Tyne. She was severely damaged and was beached.<ref name=Times091062>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Fearful Steamboat Collision |date=9 October 1862 |page_number=9 |issue=24372 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=CM091062>{{Cite news |title=Terrible Steamboat Disaster on the Tyne |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=9 October 1862 |issue=22857 }}</ref><ref name=NC101062>{{Cite news |title=Collision on the River Tyne |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=10 October 1862 |issue=9798 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Kate McLea'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was sighted off \"Bic Island\", [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]] whilst on a voyage from [[Montreal]], Province of Canada to [[Exeter]], [[Devon]]. No further trace, presumed foundered with the loss of all hands.<ref name=DC251262>{{Cite news |title=Dundee Shipping |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=25 December 1862 |issue=2925 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Libra''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] {{convert|200|nmi|km}} from [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt Eyalet|Egypt]]. Her crew survived. She was on a voyage from Alexandria to [[Falmouth, Cornwall]].<ref name=Times091062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship foundered off the north coast of [[No