itish North America]] ({{coord|41|32|47|N|59|17|45|W|name=''Lamplighter''}}) by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Alabama|CSS ''Alabama'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America}}).<ref name=macslogalabama/><ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref name=gainesp32/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lilias''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Red Island]], [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]], [[British North America]]. She was on a voyage from [[Porthmadog|Port Madoc]], [[Caernarfonshire]] to [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], British North America.<ref name=Times281062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lone Star''\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War, Union blockade: The [[schooner]] was burned at [[Taylor's Bayou]], [[Texas]], by boat crews from the [[gunboat]] {{USS|Rachel Seaman|1861|6}} and the armed [[Steamship|steamer]] {{USS|Kensington|1862|6}} (both {{navy|United States|1861}}).<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref name=gainesp170>Gaines, p. 170.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Margaret and Ann''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned off [[Strumble Head]], [[Pembrokeshire]]. Her crew survived. She was on a voyage from [[Maryport]], [[Cumberland]] to [[Saint-Valery-sur-Somme]], [[Somme (department)|Somme]], France.<ref name=Times181062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Orion'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground at [[Neath]], [[Glamorgan]].<ref name=LM171062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pauline Cornelia''\n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore on [[Gransk\u00e4r]], [[Grand Duchy of Finland]]. She was on a voyage from [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to an English port. She was refloated on 18 October and taken in to [[Helsinki]], Grand Duchy of Finland.<ref name=Times181062>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=18 October 1862 |page_number=11 |issue=24380 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=S301062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ramonita'' \n|flag=[[File:Gdansk flag.svg|22px]] [[Danzig]] \n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on Smith's Knoll, in the North Sea off the coast of [[Norfolk]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was on a voyage from [[Alloa]], [[Clackmannanshire]], United Kingdom to [[New York City|New York]], United States. She was refloated and taken in to [[Great Yarmouth]], Norfolk in a leaky condition.<ref name=S181062/><ref name=AL1862>{{cite journal |url=https://research.mysticseaport.org/item/l0237571862/353/ |title=Brigs |journal=American Lloyd's Register of American and Foreign Shipping 1862 |year=1862 |publisher=American Lloyds |location=New York}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Stonewall''\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States|1861}}\n|desc=American Civil War, Union blockade: The [[schooner]] was burned at Taylor's Bayou by boat crews from the [[gunboat]] {{USS|Rachel Seaman|1861|6}} and the armed [[Steamship|steamer]] {{USS|Kensington|1862|6}} (both {{navy|United States|1861}}).<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1862/><ref name=gainesp172>Gaines, p. 172.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Yarmouth''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked near \"Warberg\", Sweden. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Stettin]].<ref name=Times171062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==16 October==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=16 October 1862 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Europa'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Gunfleet Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Essex]].<ref name=LM171062/> She was on a voyage from [[Archangelsk]], Russia to London.<ref name=S221062a/> She was refloated on 20 October and towed in to [[Harwich]], Essex.<ref name=S231062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Favourite'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] was wrecked on \"North Faro Island\". Her crew were rescued.<ref name=LM301062>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=30 October 1862 |issue=4593 }}</ref><ref name=S301062>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=30 October 1862 |issue=11924 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ida Albertina''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] ran aground on the Middelgrund, off the Danish coast. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to the \"Nieu Diep\". She was refloated the next day and resumed her voyage.<ref name=S221062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lecolme'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[yacht]] was driven ashore in [[Lough Deary]]. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=S251062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Louise''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship collided with {{HMS|Eclipse|1860|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) in the [[English Channel]] off [[Beachy Head]], [[Sussex]] and was abandoned. Her crew were rescued by HMS ''Eclipse''. ''Louise'' was on a voyage from [[Swansea]], [[Glamorgan]] to [[Hastings]], Sussex. She was taken in to [[Ramsgate]], [[Kent]] in a derelict condition the next day.<ref name=Times241062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Oak''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was wrecked near [[Solva]], [[Pembrokeshire]]. Her five crew were rescued by [[Manby Mortar|rocket apparatus]]. She was on a voyage from [[Troon]], [[Ayrshire]] to [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]].<ref name=Times201062/><ref name=DC221062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Portland'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] ran aground on the Whitby Rock. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Retreiver'' \n|flag={{flagcount