 pp. 151-152.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Nelson'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was driven into the lock gates and damaged at North Shields.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Northumberland'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was driven ashore in the [[River Lune]].<ref name=LM211062b>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=20 October 1862 |issue=4585 }}</ref> She was on a voyage from a port in British North America to [[Glasson Dock]], Lancashire.<ref name=S221062a/> She was refloated on 22 October and towed in to Glasson Dock.<ref name=S231062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Nymph'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore between Breaksea Point and Sully Island. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], Glamorgan to [[Nantes]], [[Loire-Inf\u00e9rieure]].<ref name=S221062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Othello'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was damaged in the River Tyne.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Panope'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was damaged at North Shields.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Penningham'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was abandoned on the [[Kentish Knock (England)|Kentish Knock]]. All on board were rescued by the [[steamship]] ''Feyenoord'' ({{flag|Netherlands}}). ''Penningham'' was on a voyage from Jamaica to London.<ref name=DC221062/><ref name=S221062>{{Cite news |title=The Great Gale. - More Calamitous Losses |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=22 October 1862 |issue=11917 |page=6 }}</ref> She was discovered derelict {{convert|15|nmi|km}} off [[North Foreland]], Kent by ''Ocean'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}), which put a skeleton crew aboard, as did a [[steamship]]. She subsequently foundered {{convert|1.5|nmi|km}} off the ''[[Galloper Lightship]]'' ([[File:Trinity House Ensign (pre-1937).svg|22px]] [[Trinity House]]).<ref name=Times231062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Perlew'' \n|flag={{flag|Norway|1844}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was damaged at South Shields.<ref name=S221062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pilot'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[tugboat|tug]] was damaged in the River Tyne.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Port Glasgow''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] ran aground on the Sizewell Bank, in the North Sea off the coast of Suffolk and was wrecked. Her crew were rescued by [[Manby Mortar|rocket apparatus]]. She was on a voyage from [[Warkworth, Northumberland]] to [[Boulogne-sur-Mer|Boulogne]], [[Pas-de-Calais]], France.<ref name=Times211062/><ref name=Times221062/><ref name=S211062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Premier'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was abandoned in the Atlantic Ocean. Her crew were rescued by ''Ganges'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Premier'' was on a voyage from New York to [[Tralee]], [[County Kerry]].<ref name=S221162>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=22 November 1862 |issue=11944 |page=7 }}</ref><ref name=AJ251162>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Aberdeen Journal |location=Aberdeen |date=25 November 1862 |issue=5994 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pujeno'' \n|flag={{flag|Kingdom of Hanover|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] was driven ashore near [[Stettin]]. She was on a voyage from Newcastle upon Tyne to [[Stralsund]]. She was refloated and towed in to [[Helsing\u00f8r]], Denmark in a leaky condition.<ref name=NC311062/><ref name=S011162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Quiasa Rosa''\n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Formby]], Lancashire with the loss of all hands.<ref name=Times221062/><ref name=Times231062a/><ref name=SI221062>{{Cite news |title=The Storm - Further Particulars |newspaper=Sheffield Independent |location=Sheffield |date=22 October 1862 |issue=2507 |page=3 |volume=43 }}</ref><ref name=DN231062/> She was on a voyage from [[Ardrossan]], [[Ayrshire]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] to [[Genoa]].<ref name=Times251062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Queen'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was severely damaged at South Shields.<ref name=S221062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{PS|Robert and Anne|1843|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[tugboat|tug]] sank in the River Tyne.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Robert and Mary''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] sank in the [[River Tyne]].<ref name=Times221062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Sandfly|1855|6}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The {{sclass-|Albacore|gunboat}} was severely damaged at North Shields when a Dutch [[barque]] drove into her.<ref name=S211062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sceptre'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was damaged at South Shields.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sea Nymph'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on Scroby Sands and sank.<ref name=LM211062b/> Her crew were rescued by ''Orion'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}.<ref name=S211062a/><ref name=NC311062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sir Allen McNab''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked on the French coast. Her crew were rescued by the [[steamship]] ''Emerald'' ({{flag|Belgium}}). ''Sir Allen Mcnab'' was on a voyage from [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]] to London.<ref name=Times221062>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Gale |date=22 October 1862 |page_number=10 |issue=24383 |column=E }}</ref><ref name=NC311062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sir Henry Parnell''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was driven ashore at South Shields.<ref name=Times221062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sisters'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was severely damaged in the [[Pool of London]] when tow other vessels broke their moorings and ran into her.<ref name=LM251062a>{{Cite news |title=The Storm |newspaper=Leeds Mercury |location=Leeds |date=25 October 1862 |issue=7656 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Spring'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was damaged at South Shields.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sumner'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was driven from her moorings and damaged at South Shields.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Thetis''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship capsized in the North Sea with the loss of seven of her eleven crew. She was on a voyage from [[Sundsvall]], Norway to [[Exmouth]], [[Devon]].<ref name=Times011162/><ref name=Times081162>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=8 November 1862 |page_number=11 |issue=24398 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Triton'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was severely damaged at South Shields.<ref name=S221062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Tramp'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[tugboat|tug]] sank in the River Tyne.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Two Brothers''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] foundered in the North Sea {{convert|8|nmi|km}} north of the ''[[Dudgeon Lightship]]'' ([[File:Trinity House Ensign (pre-1937).svg|22px]] [[Trinity House]]). A crew member was rescued by a foreign [[schooner]]. Three people were rescued by the schooner ''Susannah'' ({{Flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=Times221062/> She was on a voyage from Newcastle upon Tyne to London.<ref name=NC071162/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Urania'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] probably foundered in the North Sea with the loss of all four crew. A [[message in a bottle]] washed up on the Norwegian coast on 30 December. The message stated that it was feared she would sink. She was on a voyage from Sunderland to Dundee.<ref name=DC190163>{{Cite news |title=Dundee Shipping |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=19 January 1863 |issue=2946 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Useful''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] capsized and sank at South Shields.<ref name=Times221062/><ref name=S221062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Violet'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] ran aground on the Pan Sand, off the north Kent coast. She was subsequently taken in to Margate in a derelict condition by the Margate Lifeboat.<ref name=S221062a>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=22 October 1862 |issue=11917 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Volusia''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked at [[Flamborough Head]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from South Shields to Great Yarmouth.<ref name=Times211062/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Water Kelpie'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was damaged in the River Tyne.<ref name=NC241062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Waterlily''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Rattray Head]], [[Aberdeenshire]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from New York to Leith.<ref name=Times231062a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''William and Ann'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] 