{"title_page": "Kenai Fjords National Park", "text_new": "{{use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{use American English|dateNational Park\n| map = Alaska#North America\n| relief = 1\n| map_caption = Location in Alaska##Location in North America\n| location = [[Kenai Peninsula Borough, Alaska|Kenai Peninsula Borough]], [[Alaska]], United States\n| nearest_city = [[Seward, Alaska|Seward]]\n| coordinates = {{coords|59|55|04|N|149|59|15|W|display=inline, title}}\n| area_acre = 669984\n| area_ref = <ref name=\"area\">{{NPS area|year=2011|accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref>\n| established = December 2, 1980\n| visitation_num = 321,596\n| visitation_year = 2018\n| visitation_ref = <ref name=\"visits\">{{NPS Visitation|accessdate=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n| governing_body = [[National Park Service]]\n| website = {{Official website}}\n}}\n'''Kenai Fjords National Park''' is an American [[national park]] established in 1980 by the [[Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act]]. The park covers an area of {{convert|669,984|acre|sqmi km2|1}}<ref name=\"area\"/> on the [[Kenai Peninsula]] in south-central [[Alaska]], near the town of [[Seward, Alaska|Seward]]. The park contains the [[Harding Icefield]], one of the largest [[ice field]]s in the United States. The park is named for the numerous [[fjord]]s carved by glaciers moving down the mountains from the ice field. The field is the source of at least 38 glaciers, the largest of which is Bear Glacier. The fjords are glacial valleys that have been submerged below sea level by a combination of rising sea levels and land subsidence. The park lies just to the west of Seward, a cruise ship port. [[Exit Glacier]] is a popular destination at the end of the park's only road. The remainder of the park is accessible by boat,<ref>[https://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/water-taxis.htm \"Kenai Fjords National Park: Water Taxi\"]. ''nps.gov''. National Park Service. January 31, 2018. Retrieved July 12, 2018.</ref> airplane,<ref>[https://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/air-taxi.htm \"Kenai Fjords National Park: Air Taxi\"]. ''nps.gov''. National Park Service. February 2, 2018. Retrieved July 12, 2018.</ref> and hiking.\n\nKenai Fjords National Monument was initially designated by President [[Jimmy Carter]] on December 1, 1978, using the [[Antiquities Act]], pending final legislation to resolve the allotment of public lands in Alaska. Establishment as a national park followed the passage of the Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act in 1980. The park protects the icefield, a narrow fringe of forested land between the mountains and the sea, and the deeply indented coastline. The park is inhabited by a variety of terrestrial and marine mammals, including [[Alaska Peninsula brown bear|brown]] and [[American black bear|black bears]], [[Alaska moose|moose]], [[sea otter]]s, [[harbor seal]]s, [[Humpback whale|humpback]] and [[killer whale]]s.\n\n==History==\nKenai Fjords National Park was established in 1980 by the [[Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act]] (ANILCA).<ref>Catton, p. 2.</ref> It is a relatively small and accessible park by Alaskan national park standards, about 88% as big as [[Yosemite National Park]]. It is the fifth most-visited park in Alaska, but the 11th of 13 Alaska parks in area, and is the closest national park to Anchorage. The park's headquarters is in Seward.<ref>Catton, pp. 3\u20134.</ref> It is the only Alaska national park that did not originally allow subsistence use by Native Americans, but native village corporations continue to have interests in [[inholding]]s within the park,<ref>Catton, p. 5.</ref> and have since established subsistence rights on those properties.<ref name=catton213217>Catton, pp. 213\u2013217.</ref>\n\n===Human habitation===\nAt the time of the park's establishment, there were few permanent inhabitants.<ref name=catton9394>Catton, pp. 93\u201394.</ref> Archeological surveys have altered the early view that the area was subject to only transient occupation as evidence has accumulated of long-term use. It is believed that coastal subsidence and rising water levels have inundated many sites, as the shoreline was the place richest in resources for early peoples.<ref name=catton197198>Catton, pp. 197\u2013198.</ref> A 1993 Park Service survey documented several village sites dated between 1200 AD and 1920. The survey also found evidence that an earthquake dating to about 1170 AD lowered the shoreline by at least {{convert|1.8|m|ft}}, potentially inundating earlier sites. A 2003 follow-up survey indicated that one site was occupied between 950 AD and 1800. Another site was used from 1785 to 1820. A third site showed occupancy from 1850 to 1890.<ref name=catton197198/>\n\nSeveral gold mines from historical times have been documented in the park.<ref name=catton9394/> Mining activity centered on Nuka Bay. Some sites had been active into the 1980s. Eleven mine sites have been documented and two of the mine sites have been determined to be eligible for the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>Catton, pp. 201\u2013203.</ref>\n\n===Proposals for a Kenai Fjords park===\nEarly studies of possible new Park Service units in Alaska took place in the 1930s and 1940s.  The first study, entitled ''Alaska - Its Resources and Development'' was centered on the development of tourism, despite a dissent from co-author [[Bob Marshall (wilderness activist)|Bob Marshall]], who advocated strict preservation.<ref>Catton, p. 25.</ref> Another study, funded as part of the [[Alaska Highway]] in the 1940s drew similar conclusions to the first study's majority opinion. In 1964 [[George B. Hartzog Jr.]], director of the National Park Service, initiated a new study entitled ''Operation Great Land'', advocating the development and promotion of the existing Alaska parks.<ref>Catton, pp. 25\u201327.</ref> Follow-up action by Hartzog brought the Park Service into discussions over the [[Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act]] (ANCSA). The Kenai Fjords area was not considered to be of the first priority for park designation under the ANCSA.<ref>Catton, pp. 27\u201329.</ref>\n\n[[File:Kenai Fjords - Aialik Glacier.jpg|thumb|Aialik Glacier]]\nThe earliest proposals for a national park at the Kenai Fjords was raised in the 1970s. In 1971 the Seward National Recreation Area was proposed for the area between the head of Resurrection Bay and Turnagain Arm, extending east to [[Whittier, Alaska|Whittier]] and west to Exit Glacier. This proposal allowed logging and mining in the area. Although the proposal had support in Congress and from the [[US Forest Service]] and the [[Bureau of Land Management]], it was overcome by difficulties with native land claims.<ref>Catton, pp. 22\u201323.</ref> Internal Park Service documents envisioned an {{convert|800000|acre|sqmi km2|1|adj=on}} park protecting the coast and the icefield, but this conflicted with the Seward National Recreation Area and a proposed expansion of the Kenai National Moose Range. Another proposal placed the Aialik Peninsula under [[US Fish and Wildlife Service]]  jurisdiction. On March 15, 1972, four areas of the Kenai Peninsula were set aside under the ANCSA for federal protected areas.<ref>Catton, p. 32.</ref> The same day the National Park Service formed an Alaska Task Force to study proposed park lands. The Kenai Fjords region was designated Study Area 11. Negotiations between the Park Service, Forest Service, Fish and Wildlife Service and the [[Chugach Alaska Corporation]] resulted in a decision by the Department of the Interior to make the Park Service the lead agency for the Kenai Fjords area. In 1973 the Nixon administration proposed the Harding Icefield\u2013Kenai Fjords National Monument as part of the ANILCA legislation. The proposed monument totaled {{convert|300000|acre|sqmi km2|1}} in three areas: the icefield and two island groups.<ref>Catton, pp. 33\u201335.</ref>\n\nLegislation stalled in Congress during the [[Watergate scandal]], and was not pursued again until the Carter administration. Secretary of the Interior [[Cecil D. Andrus]] proposed a {{convert|410000|acre|sqmi km2|1|adj=on}} Kenai Fjords National Park.<ref>Catton, p. 47.</ref> Alaskan opposition to ANILCA prompted President [[Jimmy Carter]] to proclaim Kenai Fjords National Monument under the provisions of the [[Antiquities Act]] on December 1, 1978, pending final passage of an Alaskan lands bill.<ref>Catton, p. 55.</ref> No visitor facilities or full-time local management structure resulted from the monument's proclamation. A single ranger was assigned to Seward as a local liaison.<ref>Catton, pp. 58\u201359.</ref>\n\n===National park===\n[[File:1055 - exit glacier.jpg|thumb|Exit Glacier]]\nOn December 2, 1980, the ANILCA bill was signed into law by Jimmy Carter, converting Kenai Fjords to a national park.<ref>Catton, pp. 59\u201360.</ref> The first park improvements focused on improving access to Exit Glacier.<ref>Catton, pp. 66\u201367.</ref> In 1982, a general management plan for the park was finalized, designating Exit Glacier as \"front-country,\" the fjords as \"back-country,\" and the icefield as wilderness.<ref>Catton, pp. 73\u201374.</ref> The park was initially administered by a small cadre of permanent and seasonal rangers and technicians who put considerable emphasis on community liaison.<ref>Catton, p. 75.</ref>\n\nUnder the provisions of ANILCA the park included {{convert|119000|acre|sqmi km2|1}} of \"native selected lands,\" property that was taken out of federal ownership and conveyed to Alaskan native corporations.<ref>Catton, p. 219.</ref> Most of the lands claimed were on the coastline. {{convert|30295|acre|sqmi km2|1}} were repurchased by the Park Service in the 1990s, retaining subsistence rights on about {{convert|9000|acre|sqmi km2|1}}. This altered the original intent of the park to include subsistence claims, previously unrecognized.<ref name=catton213217/> A lodge was developed by the Port Graham community on Aialik Bay.<ref>Catton, p. 220.</ref>\n\n===Activities===\n[[File:Sailboat at the mouth of Thumb Cove, Resurrection Bay.jpg|thumb|A sailboat near the mouth of Thumb Cove, in Resurrection Bay]]\nSeward is a departure point and destination for large cruise ships from [[Celebrity Cruises]], [[Holland America Line]], [[Royal Caribbean International]] and others. Passenger traffic through Seward is projected at 68,000 for 2013.<ref name=cpi1>{{cite web|title=Seward Basics|url=http://www.cruiseportinsider.com/seward.html#.URk5MFfsYtU|publisher=CruisePortInsider|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> Cruise tours originating from Seward provide access to the park via [[Resurrection Bay]]. Various companies offer tours, many guided by [[National Park Ranger]]s. The tours provide views of land and marine wildlife, particularly [[Steller sea lion]]s, [[puffins]], [[Dall's porpoise]]s, [[American black bear]], [[snowshoe hare]]s, [[Mountain goat]]s, and [[humpback whales|humpback]] and [[orca whale]]s, as well as natural sights such as the fjords and [[tidewater glacier]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/boattours.htm |title=Boat Tours |work=Kenai Fjords National Park |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=July 11, 2009}}</ref> Seward is a destination for cruise ships. Bus tours from Seward visit Exit Glacier and boat tours visit other parts of the park<ref>Catton, pp. 135, 137\u2013138.</ref>\n\nThe park maintains public-use cabins and shelters in coastal areas and at the edge of the Harding Icefield. Some of these are on native corporation lands, with a portion of the use fee going to the native community.<ref>Catton, pp. 149\u2013150.</ref>\n\nThe park has established a cooperative relationship with the [[Alaska SeaLife Center]], exchanging interpretive services.<ref>Catton, p. 208.</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:KEFJ-Park-map1-2012.png|thumb|Map of Kenai Fjords National Park]]\nThe park lies on the southeastern side of the [[Kenai Peninsula]], about {{convert|130|mi|km}} south of Anchorage. The nearest large town is [[Seward, Alaska|Seward]], immediately to the east of the park on [[Resurrection Bay]]. The park includes the region's deeply indented glaciated coastline and its interior icefields. The most significant [[fjord]]s include [[Aialik Bay]], [[Harris Bay]], [[McCarty Fjord]] and [[Nuka Bay]]. Much of the interior is covered by the [[Harding Icefield]]. The park's highest point is an unnamed peak of {{convert|6450|ft|m}} in the [[Kenai Mountains]]. The park is bordered on the west by [[Kenai National Wildlife Refuge]] and on the south by [[Kachemak Bay State Park]].<ref name=kefjmap1>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/maps.htm|title=Kenai Fjords Map|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe park can be reached from Seward, {{convert|130|mi|km|abbr=on}} south of [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]] at the southern terminus of the [[Seward Highway]]. It is only one of three national parks in Alaska that can be reached by road, via the [[Exit Glacier]] Nature Center. A network of trails from the Nature Center provide access to the glacier, and the {{convert|7.4|mi|km|adj=on}} Harding Icefield Trail.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/exit-glacier.htm |title=Exit Glacier |work=Kenai Fjords National Park |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=July 11, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/harding_icefield_trail.htm |title=Harding Ice Field Trail |work=Kenai Fjords National Park |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=July 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Geology===\n[[File:Bear Glacier, Kenai Fjords National Park (6808652535).jpg|thumb|Bear Glacier, the longest glacier in the park]]\nThe park's landscape has been shaped by [[plate tectonics]], with the [[Pacific Plate]] [[subduction|subducting]] beneath the [[North American Plate]]. The process has lowered the elevation of the Kenai Mountains, gradually pulling glacial features down into the sea, which is at the same time rising. The floors of the fjords can be from {{convert|600|to|1000|ft|m}} below the present sea level.<ref name=npskefj8>{{cite web|title=Fjord Estuary Ecosystem|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/fjord-estuary-ecosystem.htm|work=Keai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> The motion of the North Pacific Plate has accreted a variety of [[terrane]]s against  the shoreline, so that the coastal region is a mixture of rocks that originated elsewhere, together with local [[igneous rock]].<ref name=npskefj3>{{cite web|title=Geologic Formations|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/geologicformations.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> Predominant rock types include shale and [[graywacke]], with [[Greenschist|greenstone]], [[tuff]] and [[chert]].<ref name=npsakso1>{{cite web|title=Kenai Fjords National Park|url=http://www.nps.gov/akso/akarc/cr_kefj.htm|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 24, 2013}}</ref> The erosive power of the glaciers produces sediment as [[rock flour]] coloring the waters around the toes of glaciers, carrying minerals into the ecosystem that support [[phytoplankton]], which in turn sustain larger animals.<ref name=npskefj8/>\n\nKenai Fjords is extensively glaciated, with 51% of the park covered by ice. The Harding Icefield receives {{convert|60|ft|m}} of snowfall per year.<ref name=npskefj6>{{cite web|title=Glaciers/Glacial Features|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/glaciers.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> More than thirty glaciers originate in the icefield, which first formed about 23,000 years ago. Icefield coverage has declined, with a 3% reduction in coverage over a 16-year study period.<ref name=npskefj7>{{cite web|title=The Harding Icefield|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/the-harding-icefield.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> The park's largest glacier is Bear Glacier. The most accessible glacier, and the only portion of the park accessible by road, is [[Exit Glacier]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/index.htm |title=Nature & Science |work=Kenai Fjords National Park |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=July 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\n\nAccording to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system, Kenai Fjords National Park has a [[Subarctic climate]] (''Dfc'') with cool summers and year around precipitation. According to the [[United States Department of Agriculture]], the Plant [[Hardiness zone]] at Exit Glacier Visitor Center at 463 ft (141 m) elevation is 4b with an average annual extreme minimum temperature of -20.3&nbsp;\u00b0F (-29.1&nbsp;\u00b0C). <ref name=\"USDA\">{{cite web|url=https://planthardiness.ars.usda.gov/PHZMWeb/InteractiveMap.aspx|publisher=[[United States Department of Agriculture]]|accessdate=2019-07-12|title=USDA Interactive Plant Hardiness Map}}</ref>\n\n==Wildlife and ecology==\n[[File:2011 Kenai Fjords Sea Otter-3 (6009163594).jpg|thumb|[[Sea otter]], Kenai Fjords ]]\n[[File:LMazzuca Fin Whale.jpg|thumb|[[Fin whale]] in Kenai Fjords ]]\n[[File:Harding Icefield 1.jpg|thumb|Harding Icefield]]\nKenai Fjords National Park is dominated by a glaciated landscape. The park's glaciers have retreated through the twentieth century, exposing new lands to colonization by plant and animal life. The park also features a significant marine environment.<ref name=npskefj2>{{cite web|title=Nature & Science|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/index.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLarge terrestrial mammal species in the park include [[Northwestern wolf|timber wolf]], [[North American porcupine|porcupine]], [[Canada lynx|lynx]], [[Grizzly bear|brown bear]],<ref name=npskefj12>{{cite web|title=Brown Bear - ''Ursus Arctos''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/brown-bear.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[American black bear|black bear]]s,<ref name=npskefj11>{{cite web|title=Black Bear - ''Ursus americanus''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/black-bear.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[Alaska moose|moose]]<ref name=npskefj13>{{cite web|title=Moose - ''Alces alces gigas''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/moose.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> and [[mountain goat]].<ref name=npskefj14>{{cite web|title=Mountain Goat - ''Oreamnos americanus''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/mountain-goat.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>Catton, pp. 88-89.</ref> Smaller mammals include [[coyote]], [[North American beaver|beaver]] and [[North American river otter|river otter]]. Marine mammals include [[sea otter]],<ref name=npskefj15>{{cite web|title=Sea Otter - ''Enhydra lutris''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/sea-otter.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[harbor seal]]<ref name=npskefj17>{{cite web|title=Harbor Seal - ''Phoca vitulina''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/harbor-seal.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> and [[Steller sea lion]].<ref name=\"npskefj10\">{{cite web|title=Steller Sea Lion - ''Eumetopias jubatus''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/steller-sea-lion.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"npskefj10\"/><ref>Catton, pp. 91, 116.</ref> [[Cetacea]]ns seen in park waters include [[killer whale|orca]],<ref name=npskefj20a>{{cite web|title=Killer Whale - ''Orcinus orca''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/killer-whale.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[fin whale]],<ref name=npskefj23a>{{cite web|title=Fin Whale - ''Balaenoptera physalus''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/fin-whale.htm|work=Kenai Fjords Nation al Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[humpback whale]],<ref name=npskefj22a>{{cite web|title=Humpback Whale - ''Megaptera novaenglia''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/humpback-whale.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[minke whale]]s,<ref name=npskefj21a>{{cite web|title=Minke Whale - ''Balaenoptera acutorostrata''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/minke-whale.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[Dall's porpoise]]<ref name=npskefj19>{{cite web|title=Dall's Porpoise - ''Phocoenoides dalli''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/dalls-porpoise.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> and [[Pacific white-sided dolphin]].<ref name=npskefj18>{{cite web|title=Pacific White-Sided Dolphin - ''Lagenorhynchus Obliquidens''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/pacific-white-sided-dolphin.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBirds that nest in this park include [[bald eagle]],<ref name=npskefj20b>{{cite web|title=Bald Eagle - ''Haliaeetus leucocephalus''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/bald-eagle.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> the [[Peale's falcon|Peale's subspecies]] of [[peregrine falcon]],<ref name=npskefj23b>{{cite web|title=Peale's Peregrine Falcon|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/peregrine-falcon.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> [[black-billed magpie]],<ref name=npskefj21b>{{cite web|title=Black-Billed Magpie|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/black-billed-magpie.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> and [[Steller's jay]].<ref name=npskefj22b>{{cite web|title=Steller's Jay|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/stellers-jay.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> Marine birds include [[tufted puffin|tufted]] and [[horned puffin]],<ref name=npskefj25a>{{cite web|title=Tufted Puffin and Horned Puffin - ''Fratercula cirrhata'' and ''Fratercula corniculata''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/puffins.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> [[common murre|common]] and [[thick-billed murre]],<ref name=npskefj26>{{cite web|title=Common Murre and Thick-Billed Murre - ''Uria aalge'' and ''Uria lomvia''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/murres.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> and [[marbled murrelet]]s.<ref name=npskefj27>{{cite web|title=Marbled Murrelet|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/marbled-murrelet.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe plant communities at Kenai Fjords are shaped by glacial retreat. New lands exposed in former glacier beds are at first stony, lacking in soil. The first plants to appear in recently glaciated areas are lichens and mosses, with a few hardy plants such as [[Chamerion angustifolium|dwarf fireweed]] and [[Dryas drummondii|yellow dryas]]. These pioneers are followed by other plants as the moss and lichen break rock down into soil. In particular, [[Alnus crispa|Sitka alder]] is capable of [[nitrogen fixation|fixing nitrogen]], supporting itself and enriching the soil. Willows also appear at this stage. Willows and alders are followed by [[Populus trichocarpa|black cottonwoods]], then [[Picea sitchensis|Sitka spruce]]. The mature forest features Sitka spruce and [[Tsuga mertensiana|mountain hemlocks]], with an understory of [[devil's club]], [[Vacciium ovalifolium|Alaska blueberry]], [[Sambucus racemosa|elderberry]], [[Actaea rubra|baneberry]], [[Streptopus amplexfolius|watermelon berry]] and [[Athyrium filix-femina|lady fern]] in the coniferous forest understory. A similar succession pattern is seen at the park's [[nunatak]]s, exposed rock outcroppings in the Harding Icefield. Forested portions of the park are dominated by conifers, with deciduous forests confined to areas recently vacated by glaciers.<ref name=npskefj25b>{{cite web|title=Plant Communities|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/plant-communities.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref name=npskefj24>{{cite web|title=Plant Succession|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/plant-succession.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHarsh conditions at higher altitudes limit tree growth above the [[tree line]], creating an alpine ecosystem. The tree line at Kenai Fjords is between {{convert|750|and|1000|ft|m}} above sea level. The alpine regions support shrubby grown to alders, devil's club, elderberry, lady fern, [[cow parsnip]] and other plants. Herbaceous plants can grow in areas with better soils, supporting grasses, [[Lupinus nootkatensis|Nootka lupine]], [[fireweed]] and other perennial plants. Higher alpine regions support a dwarf shrub community less than {{convert|1|ft|cm}} high, at a very slow rate of growth. Dwarf plants in this region include [[Vaccinium uliginosium|bog blueberry]], [[Luetkea pectinata|partridgefoot]], [[Empetrum nigrum|black crowberry]] and [[Phyllodoce aleutica|Aleutian mountainheath]], all of which are vulnerable to damage from foot traffic.<ref name=npskefj25a/><ref name=npskefj25b/>\n\n===''Exxon Valdez'' oil spill===\nThe grounding of the oil tanker ''[[Exxon Valdez]]'' in [[Prince William Sound]] on March 24, 1989, produced [[Exxon Valdez oil spill|extensive contamination]] of the Kenai Fjords coastline. By early April, Park Service personnel established oil containment boom lines across the mouths of salmon streams and conducted preliminary inventories of plants and animals that might be affected by the oil. The first oil arrived on April 10. In time, about {{convert|20|mi|km}} of coastline was oiled, amounting to about 4% of the total coastline. Headlands were the most affected areas. The oil did not reach the fjords, repelled by heavy spring water flows from the land.<ref>Catton, pp. 119\u2013126.</ref> Clean-up was difficult, as the oil became a tarry emulsion that could not be skimmed, and had to be dredged. The first season's work stopped in September. Work resumed the next year and continued in 1991. That year Exxon settled with the federal and Alaskan governments, paying about $870 million into a restoration fund, some of which was earmarked for Kenai Fjords.<ref>Catton, pp. 127\u2013130.</ref>\n\nArcheological sites were also affected by the oil. A beach site near MacArthur Pass was discovered during cleanup operations. The site showed that contrary to earlier beliefs, portions of the park had been used over a long term by native peoples. The site proved to be particularly challenging to clean up without disturbing the area.<ref name=catton197198/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of birds of Kenai Fjords National Park]]\n*[[List of national parks of the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Catton, Theodore (2010), [https://web.archive.org/web/20180316153212/https://www.nps.gov/kefj/learn/historyculture/upload/A-Fragile-Beauty-AdminHistory-of-KEFJ.pdf ''A Fragile Beauty: An Administrative History of Kenai Fjords National Park''] ([[Internet Archive]]), [[National Park Service]]\n* Cook, Linda; Norris, Frank (1998), [https://web.archive.org/web/20140114153931/https://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/kefj/hrs/hrs.htm ''A Stern and Rock-Bound Coast: Kenai Fjords National Park Historic Resource Study''] (Internet Archive), National Park Service\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kenai Fjords National Park}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Kenai Fjords National Park}}\n* {{Official website}} of the [https://www.nps.gov/index.htm National Park Service]\n* [https://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/maps.htm Park maps]\n\n{{National parks of the United States}}\n{{Protected areas of Alaska}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:ANILCA establishments]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Fjords of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Kenai Fjords National Park| ]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Kenai Peninsula Borough, Alaska]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{use American English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Kenai Fjords National Park\n| iucn_category = II\n| photo = Kenai5.jpg\n| photo_caption = Bear Glacier Lake in Kenai Fjords National Park\n| map = Alaska#North America\n| relief = 1\n| map_caption = Location in Alaska##Location in North America\n| location = [[Kenai Peninsula Borough, Alaska|Kenai Peninsula Borough]], [[Alaska]], United States\n| nearest_city = [[Seward, Alaska|Seward]]\n| coordinates = {{coords|59|55|04|N|149|59|15|W|display=inline, title}}\n| area_acre = 669984\n| area_ref = <ref name=\"area\">{{NPS area|year=2011|accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref>\n| established = December 2, 1980\n| visitation_num = 321,596\n| visitation_year = 2018\n| visitation_ref = <ref name=\"visits\">{{NPS Visitation|accessdate=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n| governing_body = [[National Park Service]]\n| website = {{Official website}}\n}}\n'''Kenai Fjords National Park''' is an American [[national park]] established in 1980 by the [[Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act]]. The park covers an area of {{convert|669,984|acre|sqmi km2|1}}<ref name=\"area\"/> on the [[Kenai Peninsula]] in south-central [[Alaska]], near the town of [[Seward, Alaska|Seward]]. The park contains the [[Harding Icefield]], one of the largest [[ice field]]s in the United States. The park is named for the numerous [[fjord]]s carved by glaciers moving down the mountains from the ice field. The field is the source of at least 38 glaciers, the largest of which is Bear Glacier. The fjords are glacial valleys that have been submerged below sea level by a combination of rising sea levels and land subsidence. The park lies just to the west of Seward, a cruise ship port. [[Exit Glacier]] is a popular destination at the end of the park's only road. The remainder of the park is accessible by boat,<ref>[https://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/water-taxis.htm \"Kenai Fjords National Park: Water Taxi\"]. ''nps.gov''. National Park Service. January 31, 2018. Retrieved July 12, 2018.</ref> airplane,<ref>[https://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/air-taxi.htm \"Kenai Fjords National Park: Air Taxi\"]. ''nps.gov''. National Park Service. February 2, 2018. Retrieved July 12, 2018.</ref> and hiking.\n\nKenai Fjords National Monument was initially designated by President [[Jimmy Carter]] on December 1, 1978, using the [[Antiquities Act]], pending final legislation to resolve the allotment of public lands in Alaska. Establishment as a national park followed the passage of the Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act in 1980. The park protects the icefield, a narrow fringe of forested land between the mountains and the sea, and the deeply indented coastline. The park is inhabited by a variety of terrestrial and marine mammals, including [[Alaska Peninsula brown bear|brown]] and [[American black bear|black bears]], [[Alaska moose|moose]], [[sea otter]]s, [[harbor seal]]s, [[Humpback whale|humpback]] and [[killer whale]]s.\n\n==History==\nKenai Fjords National Park was established in 1980 by the [[Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act]] (ANILCA).<ref>Catton, p. 2.</ref> It is a relatively small and accessible park by Alaskan national park standards, about 88% as big as [[Yosemite National Park]]. It is the fifth most-visited park in Alaska, but the 11th of 13 Alaska parks in area, and is the closest national park to Anchorage. The park's headquarters is in Seward.<ref>Catton, pp. 3\u20134.</ref> It is the only Alaska national park that did not originally allow subsistence use by Native Americans, but native village corporations continue to have interests in [[inholding]]s within the park,<ref>Catton, p. 5.</ref> and have since established subsistence rights on those properties.<ref name=catton213217>Catton, pp. 213\u2013217.</ref>\n\n===Human habitation===\nAt the time of the park's establishment, there were few permanent inhabitants.<ref name=catton9394>Catton, pp. 93\u201394.</ref> Archeological surveys have altered the early view that the area was subject to only transient occupation as evidence has accumulated of long-term use. It is believed that coastal subsidence and rising water levels have inundated many sites, as the shoreline was the place richest in resources for early peoples.<ref name=catton197198>Catton, pp. 197\u2013198.</ref> A 1993 Park Service survey documented several village sites dated between 1200 AD and 1920. The survey also found evidence that an earthquake dating to about 1170 AD lowered the shoreline by at least {{convert|1.8|m|ft}}, potentially inundating earlier sites. A 2003 follow-up survey indicated that one site was occupied between 950 AD and 1800. Another site was used from 1785 to 1820. A third site showed occupancy from 1850 to 1890.<ref name=catton197198/>\n\nSeveral gold mines from historical times have been documented in the park.<ref name=catton9394/> Mining activity centered on Nuka Bay. Some sites had been active into the 1980s. Eleven mine sites have been documented and two of the mine sites have been determined to be eligible for the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>Catton, pp. 201\u2013203.</ref>\n\n===Proposals for a Kenai Fjords park===\nEarly studies of possible new Park Service units in Alaska took place in the 1930s and 1940s.  The first study, entitled ''Alaska - Its Resources and Development'' was centered on the development of tourism, despite a dissent from co-author [[Bob Marshall (wilderness activist)|Bob Marshall]], who advocated strict preservation.<ref>Catton, p. 25.</ref> Another study, funded as part of the [[Alaska Highway]] in the 1940s drew similar conclusions to the first study's majority opinion. In 1964 [[George B. Hartzog Jr.]], director of the National Park Service, initiated a new study entitled ''Operation Great Land'', advocating the development and promotion of the existing Alaska parks.<ref>Catton, pp. 25\u201327.</ref> Follow-up action by Hartzog brought the Park Service into discussions over the [[Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act]] (ANCSA). The Kenai Fjords area was not considered to be of the first priority for park designation under the ANCSA.<ref>Catton, pp. 27\u201329.</ref>\n\n[[File:Kenai Fjords - Aialik Glacier.jpg|thumb|Aialik Glacier]]\nThe earliest proposals for a national park at the Kenai Fjords was raised in the 1970s. In 1971 the Seward National Recreation Area was proposed for the area between the head of Resurrection Bay and Turnagain Arm, extending east to [[Whittier, Alaska|Whittier]] and west to Exit Glacier. This proposal allowed logging and mining in the area. Although the proposal had support in Congress and from the [[US Forest Service]] and the [[Bureau of Land Management]], it was overcome by difficulties with native land claims.<ref>Catton, pp. 22\u201323.</ref> Internal Park Service documents envisioned an {{convert|800000|acre|sqmi km2|1|adj=on}} park protecting the coast and the icefield, but this conflicted with the Seward National Recreation Area and a proposed expansion of the Kenai National Moose Range. Another proposal placed the Aialik Peninsula under [[US Fish and Wildlife Service]]  jurisdiction. On March 15, 1972, four areas of the Kenai Peninsula were set aside under the ANCSA for federal protected areas.<ref>Catton, p. 32.</ref> The same day the National Park Service formed an Alaska Task Force to study proposed park lands. The Kenai Fjords region was designated Study Area 11. Negotiations between the Park Service, Forest Service, Fish and Wildlife Service and the [[Chugach Alaska Corporation]] resulted in a decision by the Department of the Interior to make the Park Service the lead agency for the Kenai Fjords area. In 1973 the Nixon administration proposed the Harding Icefield\u2013Kenai Fjords National Monument as part of the ANILCA legislation. The proposed monument totaled {{convert|300000|acre|sqmi km2|1}} in three areas: the icefield and two island groups.<ref>Catton, pp. 33\u201335.</ref>\n\nLegislation stalled in Congress during the [[Watergate scandal]], and was not pursued again until the Carter administration. Secretary of the Interior [[Cecil D. Andrus]] proposed a {{convert|410000|acre|sqmi km2|1|adj=on}} Kenai Fjords National Park.<ref>Catton, p. 47.</ref> Alaskan opposition to ANILCA prompted President [[Jimmy Carter]] to proclaim Kenai Fjords National Monument under the provisions of the [[Antiquities Act]] on December 1, 1978, pending final passage of an Alaskan lands bill.<ref>Catton, p. 55.</ref> No visitor facilities or full-time local management structure resulted from the monument's proclamation. A single ranger was assigned to Seward as a local liaison.<ref>Catton, pp. 58\u201359.</ref>\n\n===National park===\n[[File:1055 - exit glacier.jpg|thumb|Exit Glacier]]\nOn December 2, 1980, the ANILCA bill was signed into law by Jimmy Carter, converting Kenai Fjords to a national park.<ref>Catton, pp. 59\u201360.</ref> The first park improvements focused on improving access to Exit Glacier.<ref>Catton, pp. 66\u201367.</ref> In 1982, a general management plan for the park was finalized, designating Exit Glacier as \"front-country,\" the fjords as \"back-country,\" and the icefield as wilderness.<ref>Catton, pp. 73\u201374.</ref> The park was initially administered by a small cadre of permanent and seasonal rangers and technicians who put considerable emphasis on community liaison.<ref>Catton, p. 75.</ref>\n\nUnder the provisions of ANILCA the park included {{convert|119000|acre|sqmi km2|1}} of \"native selected lands,\" property that was taken out of federal ownership and conveyed to Alaskan native corporations.<ref>Catton, p. 219.</ref> Most of the lands claimed were on the coastline. {{convert|30295|acre|sqmi km2|1}} were repurchased by the Park Service in the 1990s, retaining subsistence rights on about {{convert|9000|acre|sqmi km2|1}}. This altered the original intent of the park to include subsistence claims, previously unrecognized.<ref name=catton213217/> A lodge was developed by the Port Graham community on Aialik Bay.<ref>Catton, p. 220.</ref>\n\n===Activities===\n[[File:Sailboat at the mouth of Thumb Cove, Resurrection Bay.jpg|thumb|A sailboat near the mouth of Thumb Cove, in Resurrection Bay]]\nSeward is a departure point and destination for large cruise ships from [[Celebrity Cruises]], [[Holland America Line]], [[Royal Caribbean International]] and others. Passenger traffic through Seward is projected at 68,000 for 2013.<ref name=cpi1>{{cite web|title=Seward Basics|url=http://www.cruiseportinsider.com/seward.html#.URk5MFfsYtU|publisher=CruisePortInsider|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> Cruise tours originating from Seward provide access to the park via [[Resurrection Bay]]. Various companies offer tours, many guided by [[National Park Ranger]]s. The tours provide views of land and marine wildlife, particularly [[Steller sea lion]]s, [[puffins]], [[Dall's porpoise]]s, [[American black bear]], [[snowshoe hare]]s, [[Mountain goat]]s, and [[humpback whales|humpback]] and [[orca whale]]s, as well as natural sights such as the fjords and [[tidewater glacier]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/boattours.htm |title=Boat Tours |work=Kenai Fjords National Park |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=July 11, 2009}}</ref> Seward is a destination for cruise ships. Bus tours from Seward visit Exit Glacier and boat tours visit other parts of the park<ref>Catton, pp. 135, 137\u2013138.</ref>\n\nThe park maintains public-use cabins and shelters in coastal areas and at the edge of the Harding Icefield. Some of these are on native corporation lands, with a portion of the use fee going to the native community.<ref>Catton, pp. 149\u2013150.</ref>\n\nThe park has established a cooperative relationship with the [[Alaska SeaLife Center]], exchanging interpretive services.<ref>Catton, p. 208.</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:KEFJ-Park-map1-2012.png|thumb|Map of Kenai Fjords National Park]]\nThe park lies on the southeastern side of the [[Kenai Peninsula]], about {{convert|130|mi|km}} south of Anchorage. The nearest large town is [[Seward, Alaska|Seward]], immediately to the east of the park on [[Resurrection Bay]]. The park includes the region's deeply indented glaciated coastline and its interior icefields. The most significant [[fjord]]s include [[Aialik Bay]], [[Harris Bay]], [[McCarty Fjord]] and [[Nuka Bay]]. Much of the interior is covered by the [[Harding Icefield]]. The park's highest point is an unnamed peak of {{convert|6450|ft|m}} in the [[Kenai Mountains]]. The park is bordered on the west by [[Kenai National Wildlife Refuge]] and on the south by [[Kachemak Bay State Park]].<ref name=kefjmap1>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/maps.htm|title=Kenai Fjords Map|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe park can be reached from Seward, {{convert|130|mi|km|abbr=on}} south of [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]] at the southern terminus of the [[Seward Highway]]. It is only one of three national parks in Alaska that can be reached by road, via the [[Exit Glacier]] Nature Center. A network of trails from the Nature Center provide access to the glacier, and the {{convert|7.4|mi|km|adj=on}} Harding Icefield Trail.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/exit-glacier.htm |title=Exit Glacier |work=Kenai Fjords National Park |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=July 11, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/harding_icefield_trail.htm |title=Harding Ice Field Trail |work=Kenai Fjords National Park |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=July 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Geology===\n[[File:Bear Glacier, Kenai Fjords National Park (6808652535).jpg|thumb|Bear Glacier, the longest glacier in the park]]\nThe park's landscape has been shaped by [[plate tectonics]], with the [[Pacific Plate]] [[subduction|subducting]] beneath the [[North American Plate]]. The process has lowered the elevation of the Kenai Mountains, gradually pulling glacial features down into the sea, which is at the same time rising. The floors of the fjords can be from {{convert|600|to|1000|ft|m}} below the present sea level.<ref name=npskefj8>{{cite web|title=Fjord Estuary Ecosystem|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/fjord-estuary-ecosystem.htm|work=Keai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> The motion of the North Pacific Plate has accreted a variety of [[terrane]]s against  the shoreline, so that the coastal region is a mixture of rocks that originated elsewhere, together with local [[igneous rock]].<ref name=npskefj3>{{cite web|title=Geologic Formations|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/geologicformations.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> Predominant rock types include shale and [[graywacke]], with [[Greenschist|greenstone]], [[tuff]] and [[chert]].<ref name=npsakso1>{{cite web|title=Kenai Fjords National Park|url=http://www.nps.gov/akso/akarc/cr_kefj.htm|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 24, 2013}}</ref> The erosive power of the glaciers produces sediment as [[rock flour]] coloring the waters around the toes of glaciers, carrying minerals into the ecosystem that support [[phytoplankton]], which in turn sustain larger animals.<ref name=npskefj8/>\n\nKenai Fjords is extensively glaciated, with 51% of the park covered by ice. The Harding Icefield receives {{convert|60|ft|m}} of snowfall per year.<ref name=npskefj6>{{cite web|title=Glaciers/Glacial Features|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/glaciers.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> More than thirty glaciers originate in the icefield, which first formed about 23,000 years ago. Icefield coverage has declined, with a 3% reduction in coverage over a 16-year study period.<ref name=npskefj7>{{cite web|title=The Harding Icefield|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/the-harding-icefield.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> The park's largest glacier is Bear Glacier. The most accessible glacier, and the only portion of the park accessible by road, is [[Exit Glacier]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/index.htm |title=Nature & Science |work=Kenai Fjords National Park |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=July 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\n\nAccording to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system, Kenai Fjords National Park has a [[Subarctic climate]] (''Dfc'') with cool summers and year around precipitation. According to the [[United States Department of Agriculture]], the Plant [[Hardiness zone]] at Exit Glacier Visitor Center at 463 ft (141 m) elevation is 4b with an average annual extreme minimum temperature of -20.3&nbsp;\u00b0F (-29.1&nbsp;\u00b0C). <ref name=\"USDA\">{{cite web|url=https://planthardiness.ars.usda.gov/PHZMWeb/InteractiveMap.aspx|publisher=[[United States Department of Agriculture]]|accessdate=2019-07-12|title=USDA Interactive Plant Hardiness Map}}</ref>\n\n==Wildlife and ecology==\n[[File:2011 Kenai Fjords Sea Otter-3 (6009163594).jpg|thumb|[[Sea otter]], Kenai Fjords ]]\n[[File:LMazzuca Fin Whale.jpg|thumb|[[Fin whale]] in Kenai Fjords ]]\n[[File:Harding Icefield 1.jpg|thumb|Harding Icefield]]\nKenai Fjords National Park is dominated by a glaciated landscape. The park's glaciers have retreated through the twentieth century, exposing new lands to colonization by plant and animal life. The park also features a significant marine environment.<ref name=npskefj2>{{cite web|title=Nature & Science|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/index.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLarge terrestrial mammal species in the park include [[Northwestern wolf|timber wolf]], [[North American porcupine|porcupine]], [[Canada lynx|lynx]], [[Grizzly bear|brown bear]],<ref name=npskefj12>{{cite web|title=Brown Bear - ''Ursus Arctos''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/brown-bear.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[American black bear|black bear]]s,<ref name=npskefj11>{{cite web|title=Black Bear - ''Ursus americanus''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/black-bear.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[Alaska moose|moose]]<ref name=npskefj13>{{cite web|title=Moose - ''Alces alces gigas''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/moose.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> and [[mountain goat]].<ref name=npskefj14>{{cite web|title=Mountain Goat - ''Oreamnos americanus''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/mountain-goat.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>Catton, pp. 88-89.</ref> Smaller mammals include [[coyote]], [[North American beaver|beaver]] and [[North American river otter|river otter]]. Marine mammals include [[sea otter]],<ref name=npskefj15>{{cite web|title=Sea Otter - ''Enhydra lutris''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/sea-otter.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[harbor seal]]<ref name=npskefj17>{{cite web|title=Harbor Seal - ''Phoca vitulina''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/harbor-seal.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> and [[Steller sea lion]].<ref name=\"npskefj10\">{{cite web|title=Steller Sea Lion - ''Eumetopias jubatus''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/steller-sea-lion.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"npskefj10\"/><ref>Catton, pp. 91, 116.</ref> [[Cetacea]]ns seen in park waters include [[killer whale|orca]],<ref name=npskefj20a>{{cite web|title=Killer Whale - ''Orcinus orca''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/killer-whale.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[fin whale]],<ref name=npskefj23a>{{cite web|title=Fin Whale - ''Balaenoptera physalus''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/fin-whale.htm|work=Kenai Fjords Nation al Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[humpback whale]],<ref name=npskefj22a>{{cite web|title=Humpback Whale - ''Megaptera novaenglia''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/humpback-whale.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[minke whale]]s,<ref name=npskefj21a>{{cite web|title=Minke Whale - ''Balaenoptera acutorostrata''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/minke-whale.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> [[Dall's porpoise]]<ref name=npskefj19>{{cite web|title=Dall's Porpoise - ''Phocoenoides dalli''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/dalls-porpoise.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> and [[Pacific white-sided dolphin]].<ref name=npskefj18>{{cite web|title=Pacific White-Sided Dolphin - ''Lagenorhynchus Obliquidens''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/pacific-white-sided-dolphin.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBirds that nest in this park include [[bald eagle]],<ref name=npskefj20b>{{cite web|title=Bald Eagle - ''Haliaeetus leucocephalus''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/bald-eagle.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> the [[Peale's falcon|Peale's subspecies]] of [[peregrine falcon]],<ref name=npskefj23b>{{cite web|title=Peale's Peregrine Falcon|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/peregrine-falcon.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> [[black-billed magpie]],<ref name=npskefj21b>{{cite web|title=Black-Billed Magpie|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/black-billed-magpie.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> and [[Steller's jay]].<ref name=npskefj22b>{{cite web|title=Steller's Jay|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/stellers-jay.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> Marine birds include [[tufted puffin|tufted]] and [[horned puffin]],<ref name=npskefj25a>{{cite web|title=Tufted Puffin and Horned Puffin - ''Fratercula cirrhata'' and ''Fratercula corniculata''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/puffins.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> [[common murre|common]] and [[thick-billed murre]],<ref name=npskefj26>{{cite web|title=Common Murre and Thick-Billed Murre - ''Uria aalge'' and ''Uria lomvia''|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/murres.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> and [[marbled murrelet]]s.<ref name=npskefj27>{{cite web|title=Marbled Murrelet|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/marbled-murrelet.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe plant communities at Kenai Fjords are shaped by glacial retreat. New lands exposed in former glacier beds are at first stony, lacking in soil. The first plants to appear in recently glaciated areas are lichens and mosses, with a few hardy plants such as [[Chamerion angustifolium|dwarf fireweed]] and [[Dryas drummondii|yellow dryas]]. These pioneers are followed by other plants as the moss and lichen break rock down into soil. In particular, [[Alnus crispa|Sitka alder]] is capable of [[nitrogen fixation|fixing nitrogen]], supporting itself and enriching the soil. Willows also appear at this stage. Willows and alders are followed by [[Populus trichocarpa|black cottonwoods]], then [[Picea sitchensis|Sitka spruce]]. The mature forest features Sitka spruce and [[Tsuga mertensiana|mountain hemlocks]], with an understory of [[devil's club]], [[Vacciium ovalifolium|Alaska blueberry]], [[Sambucus racemosa|elderberry]], [[Actaea rubra|baneberry]], [[Streptopus amplexfolius|watermelon berry]] and [[Athyrium filix-femina|lady fern]] in the coniferous forest understory. A similar succession pattern is seen at the park's [[nunatak]]s, exposed rock outcroppings in the Harding Icefield. Forested portions of the park are dominated by conifers, with deciduous forests confined to areas recently vacated by glaciers.<ref name=npskefj25b>{{cite web|title=Plant Communities|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/plant-communities.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref name=npskefj24>{{cite web|title=Plant Succession|url=http://www.nps.gov/kefj/naturescience/plant-succession.htm|work=Kenai Fjords National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHarsh conditions at higher altitudes limit tree growth above the [[tree line]], creating an alpine ecosystem. The tree line at Kenai Fjords is between {{convert|750|and|1000|ft|m}} above sea level. The alpine regions support shrubby grown to alders, devil's club, elderberry, lady fern, [[cow parsnip]] and other plants. Herbaceous plants can grow in areas with better soils, supporting grasses, [[Lupinus nootkatensis|Nootka lupine]], [[fireweed]] and other perennial plants. Higher alpine regions support a dwarf shrub community less than {{convert|1|ft|cm}} high, at a very slow rate of growth. Dwarf plants in this region include [[Vaccinium uliginosium|bog blueberry]], [[Luetkea pectinata|partridgefoot]], [[Empetrum nigrum|black crowberry]] and [[Phyllodoce aleutica|Aleutian mountainheath]], all of which are vulnerable to damage from foot traffic.<ref name=npskefj25a/><ref name=npskefj25b/>\n\n===''Exxon Valdez'' oil spill===\nThe grounding of the oil tanker ''[[Exxon Valdez]]'' in [[Prince William Sound]] on March 24, 1989, produced [[Exxon Valdez oil spill|extensive contamination]] of the Kenai Fjords coastline. By early April, Park Service personnel established oil containment boom lines across the mouths of salmon streams and conducted preliminary inventories of plants and animals that might be affected by the oil. The first oil arrived on April 10. In time, about {{convert|20|mi|km}} of coastline was oiled, amounting to about 4% of the total coastline. Headlands were the most affected areas. The oil did not reach the fjords, repelled by heavy spring water flows from the land.<ref>Catton, pp. 119\u2013126.</ref> Clean-up was difficult, as the oil became a tarry emulsion that could not be skimmed, and had to be dredged. The first season's work stopped in September. Work resumed the next year and continued in 1991. That year Exxon settled with the federal and Alaskan governments, paying about $870 million into a restoration fund, some of which was earmarked for Kenai Fjords.<ref>Catton, pp. 127\u2013130.</ref>\n\nArcheological sites were also affected by the oil. A beach site near MacArthur Pass was discovered during cleanup operations. The site showed that contrary to earlier beliefs, portions of the park had been used over a long term by native peoples. The site proved to be particularly challenging to clean up without disturbing the area.<ref name=catton197198/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of birds of Kenai Fjords National Park]]\n*[[List of national parks of the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Catton, Theodore (2010), [https://web.archive.org/web/20180316153212/https://www.nps.gov/kefj/learn/historyculture/upload/A-Fragile-Beauty-AdminHistory-of-KEFJ.pdf ''A Fragile Beauty: An Administrative History of Kenai Fjords National Park''] ([[Internet Archive]]), [[National Park Service]]\n* Cook, Linda; Norris, Frank (1998), [https://web.archive.org/web/20140114153931/https://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/kefj/hrs/hrs.htm ''A Stern and Rock-Bound Coast: Kenai Fjords National Park Historic Resource Study''] (Internet Archive), National Park Service\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kenai Fjords National Park}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Kenai Fjords National Park}}\n* {{Official website}} of the [https://www.nps.gov/index.htm National Park Service]\n* [https://www.nps.gov/kefj/planyourvisit/maps.htm Park maps]\n\n{{National parks of the United States}}\n{{Protected areas of Alaska}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:ANILCA establishments]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Fjords of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Kenai Fjords National Park| ]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Kenai Peninsula Borough, Alaska]]\n", "name_user": "100.33.178.214", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenai_Fjords_National_Park"}
{"title_page": "Dennis E. Nolan", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Dennis Edward Nolan\n|image= Dennis E Nolan.jpg\n|image_size= 150\n|alt= \n|caption= General Dennis E. Nolan\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1872|4|22}}\n|birth_place= [[Akron, New York]]\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1956|2|24|1872|4|22}}\n|death_place= [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1896\u20131936\n|rank= [[Major general (United States)|Major General]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[First United States Army]]<br/>Second [[Corps Area]]<br/>Fifth [[Corps Area]]<br/>[[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]]<br/>55th Brigade, [[28th Infantry Division (United States)|28th Infantry Division]]\n|battles= [[Spanish\u2013American War]]<br/>[[Philippine\u2013American War]]<br/>World War I\n|awards= [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]]<br/>[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Silver Star]] (2)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= President, [[United States Military Academy]] Association of Graduates\n}}\n'''Dennis Edward Nolan''' (April 22, 1872 \u2013 February 24, 1956) was a career officer with the [[United States Army]]. He distinguished himself by heading the first modern American military combat intelligence function during [[World War I]]. Nolan served as the head football coach at the [[United States Military Academy]] in 1902, compiling a record of 6\u20131\u20131.\n\n==Early life and education ==\nBorn in [[Akron, New York]], outside of [[Buffalo, New York]], Nolan was the son of an Irish immigrant. He graduated from the [[United States Military Academy]] in 1896.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref>\n\n==Spanish\u2013American War==\nNolan was commissioned a second lieutenant and joined the Third Infantry. He served with the Sanitary Corps, during the Spanish\u2013American War.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref>\n\n==Football coaching career==\nIn 1902, Nolan coached the [[Army Black Knights football|Army football team]] to a record of 6 wins, 1 loss and 1 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=1752|title=Dennis E. Nolan|publisher=[[College Football Data Warehouse]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809061444/http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=1752|archivedate=2016-08-09}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' of 1930s noted that many contemporary generals (Nolan, [[Leon Kromer]], [[Malin Craig]], [[Paul Bunker]]) were connected by past football experience at West Point.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1935/10/16/archives/many-of-armys-football-stars-now-hold-high-rank-in-service-general.html?sq=Leon%2520Kromer&scp=4&st=cse Many of Army's Football Stars Now Hold High Rank in Service]. ''The New York Times'', October 16, 1935.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1931/08/02/archives/noted-west-point-athletes-who-have-become-generals-many-developed.html?sq=Leon%2520Kromer&scp=10&st=cse Many West Point Athletes Who Became Generals]. ''The New York Times'', August 2, 1931.</ref>\n\n==Later military career==\nDuring [[World War I]], Nolan organized the Intelligence Section for the American Expeditionary Forces' general headquarters.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref> Starting in August 1920, Nolan, then a brigadier general, served for a year as the War Department Chief of Military Intelligence Division.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1927 to 1931, Nolan was commander of Fifth [[Corps Area]], headquartered at [[Fort Hayes]] at [[Columbus, Ohio]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref> one of and geographically the largest of nine corps areas established in the continental United States for the administration of the regular army and reserves by the National Defense Act of 1920. As a corps area commander, he oversaw peacetime training for Army Reserves and the National Guard. In time of war, the corps areas would theoretically have ready made corps combat command structures in place to administer regiments of Regular Army, Reserve and National Guard. During the lean post-war and Great Depression years of military spending, he as well other corps commanders were expected to maintain good relations with the public and civilian officials.\n\nNolan accepted his final posting as commanding general of Second Corps Area, in charge of army units and facilities in New York, New Jersey, Delaware and Puerto Rico on December 1, 1931. On October 1, 1933, [[First United States Army]] was reestablished, co-located and co-staffed with Second Corps Area at Fort Jay, Governors Island, New York. Nolan became First Army's first peace time commander. Nolan ended his active duty army career upon retirement on April 30, 1936.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref>\n\n==Awards ==\nNolan received the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]], the [[Army Distinguished Service Medal]], and two [[Silver Citation Star|Silver Star Citations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=15685|title=Valor awards for Dennis Edward Nolan|publisher=}}</ref>  He also received the [[Croix de Guerre]] with Palm and the Medal of Solidaridad from Panama. He was made a [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]], a [[Commander of the Legion of Honour]], and a [[Order of the Crown (Belgium)|Commander of the Order of the Crown]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref> as well as appointments to the [[Order of the Crown of Italy]] and [[Order of the Merit of Chile|National Order of Merit]] of Chile.\n\n==Personal life ==\nNolan married Julia Grant Sharp on August 21, 1901. She was the daughter of Alexander Sharp and Ellen \"Nellie\" Dent. Nellie Dent Sharp was the sister of Ulysses S. Grant's wife [[Julia Grant|Julia Boggs Dent]]. In addition to her aunt Julia, Julia Sharp's family included uncle [[Frederick Tracy Dent]]. Dennis and Julia Nolan were the parents of two children: Dennis and Ellen Honora.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref>\n\nNolan died on February 24, 1956 in New York City,<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref> and was buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/denolan.htm|title=Dennis Edward Nolan, Major General, United States Army|first=Michael Robert|last=Patterson|publisher=}}</ref> General Nolan is a member of the [[Military Intelligence Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Army Black Knights football|Army Cadets]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1902\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | year         = [[1902 college football season|1902]]\n | name         = [[1902 Army Cadets football team|Army]]\n | overall      = 6\u20131\u20131\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Army\n | overall    = 6\u20131\u20131\n | confrecord =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 6\u20131\u20131\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype =\n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Portal|Biography|World War I}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|last=Kovach|first=Karen|title=The Life and Times of Dennis E. Nolan, 1872\u20131956: The Army's First G2|publisher=United States Army, History Office, Office of the Chief of Staff, Intelligence and Security Command|year=1998|location=Fort Belvoir, Virginia|url=http://stinet.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA357585&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf|access-date=2008-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214184325/http://stinet.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA357585&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf|archive-date=2012-02-14|url-status=dead}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-mil}}\n{{Succession box|\n title=Commanding General of the [[First United States Army]]\n|before=[[Hunter Liggett]]\n|years= 1933\u20131936\n|after= [[Fox Conner]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Army Black Knights football coach navbox}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nolan, Dennis E.}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights football coaches]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:People from Akron, New York]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Dennis Edward Nolan\n|image= Dennis E Nolan.jpg\n|image_size= 150\n|alt= \n|caption= General Dennis E. Nolan\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1872|4|22}}\n|birth_place= [[Akron, New York]]\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1956|2|24|1872|4|22}}\n|death_place= [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1896\u20131936\n|rank= [[Major general (United States)|Major General]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[First United States Army]]<br/>Second [[Corps Area]]<br/>Fifth [[Corps Area]]<br/>[[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]]<br/>55th Brigade, [[28th Infantry Division (United States)|28th Infantry Division]]\n|battles= [[Spanish\u2013American War]]<br/>[[Philippine\u2013American War]]<br/>World War I\n|awards= [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]]<br/>[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Silver Star]] (2)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= President, [[United States Military Academy]] Association of Graduates\n}}\n'''Dennis Edward Nolan''' (April 22, 1872 \u2013 February 24, 1956) was a career officer with the [[United States Army]]. He distinguished himself by heading the first modern American military combat intelligence function during [[World War I]]. Nolan served as the head football coach at the [[United States Military Academy]] in 1902, compiling a record of 6\u20131\u20131.\n\n==Early life and education ==\nBorn in [[Akron, New York]], outside of [[Buffalo, New York]], Nolan was the son of an Irish immigrant. He graduated from the [[United States Military Academy]] in 1896.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref>\n\n==Spanish\u2013American War==\nNolan was commissioned a second lieutenant and joined the Third Infantry. He served with the Sanitary Corps, during the Spanish\u2013American War.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref>\n\n==Football coaching career==\nIn 1902, Nolan coached the [[Army Black Knights football|Army football team]] to a record of 6 wins, 1 loss and 1 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=1752|title=Dennis E. Nolan|publisher=[[College Football Data Warehouse]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809061444/http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=1752|archivedate=2016-08-09}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' of 1930s noted that many contemporary generals (Nolan, [[Leon Kromer]], [[Malin Craig]], [[Paul Bunker]]) were connected by past football experience at West Point.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1935/10/16/archives/many-of-armys-football-stars-now-hold-high-rank-in-service-general.html?sq=Leon%2520Kromer&scp=4&st=cse Many of Army's Football Stars Now Hold High Rank in Service]. ''The New York Times'', October 16, 1935.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1931/08/02/archives/noted-west-point-athletes-who-have-become-generals-many-developed.html?sq=Leon%2520Kromer&scp=10&st=cse Many West Point Athletes Who Became Generals]. ''The New York Times'', August 2, 1931.</ref>\n\n==Later military career==\nDuring [[World War I]], Nolan organized the Intelligence Section for the American Expeditionary Forces' general headquarters.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref> Starting in August 1920, Nolan, then a brigadier general, served for a year as the War Department Chief of Military Intelligence Division.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1927 to 1931, Nolan was commander of Fifth [[Corps Area]], headquartered at [[Fort Hayes]] at [[Columbus, Ohio]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref> one of and geographically the largest of nine corps areas established in the continental United States for the administration of the regular army and reserves by the National Defense Act of 1920. As a corps area commander, he oversaw peacetime training for Army Reserves and the National Guard. In time of war, the corps areas would theoretically have ready made corps combat command structures in place to administer regiments of Regular Army, Reserve and National Guard. During the lean post-war and Great Depression years of military spending, he as well other corps commanders were expected to maintain good relations with the public and civilian officials.\n\nNolan accepted his final posting as commanding general of Second Corps Area, in charge of army units and facilities in New York, New Jersey, Delaware and Puerto Rico on December 1, 1931. On October 1, 1933, [[First United States Army]] was reestablished, co-located and co-staffed with Second Corps Area at Fort Jay, Governors Island, New York. Nolan became First Army's first peace time commander. Nolan ended his active duty army career upon retirement on April 30, 1936.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref>\n\n==Awards ==\nNolan received the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]], the [[Army Distinguished Service Medal]], and two [[Silver Citation Star|Silver Star Citations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=15685|title=Valor awards for Dennis Edward Nolan|publisher=}}</ref>  He also received the [[Croix de Guerre]] with Palm and the Medal of Solidaridad from Panama. He was made a [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]], a [[Commander of the Legion of Honour]], and a [[Order of the Crown (Belgium)|Commander of the Order of the Crown]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref> as well as appointments to the [[Order of the Crown of Italy]] and [[Order of the Merit of Chile|National Order of Merit]] of Chile.\n\n==Personal life ==\nNolan married Julia Grant Sharp on August 21, 1901. She was the daughter of Alexander Sharp and Ellen \"Nellie\" Dent. Nellie Dent Sharp was the sister of Ulysses S. Grant's wife [[Julia Grant|Julia Boggs Dent]]. In addition to her aunt Julia, Julia Sharp's family included uncle [[Frederick Tracy Dent]]. Dennis and Julia Nolan were the parents of two children: Dennis and Ellen Honora.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref>\n\nNolan died on February 24, 1956 in New York City,<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis Jr.|first=Henry Blaine|title=Generals in Khaki|publisher=Pentland Press, Inc.|year= 1998\n|ISBN= 1571970886|oclc=40298151|page=284}}</ref> and was buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/denolan.htm|title=Dennis Edward Nolan, Major General, United States Army|first=Michael Robert|last=Patterson|publisher=}}</ref> General Nolan is a member of the [[Military Intelligence Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Army Black Knights football|Army Cadets]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1902\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | year         = [[1902 college football season|1902]]\n | name         = [[1902 Army Cadets football team|Army]]\n | overall      = 6\u20131\u20131\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Army\n | overall    = 6\u20131\u20131\n | confrecord =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 6\u20131\u20131\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype =\n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Portal|Biography|World War I}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|last=Kovach|first=Karen|title=The Life and Times of Dennis E. Nolan, 1872-1956: The Army's First G2|publisher=United States Army, History Office, Office of the Chief of Staff, Intelligence and Security Command|year=1998|location=Fort Belvoir, Virginia|url=http://stinet.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA357585&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf|access-date=2008-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214184325/http://stinet.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA357585&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf|archive-date=2012-02-14|url-status=dead}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-mil}}\n{{Succession box|\n title=Commanding General of the [[First United States Army]]\n|before=[[Hunter Liggett]]\n|years= 1933\u20131936\n|after= [[Fox Conner]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Army Black Knights football coach navbox}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nolan, Dennis E.}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights football coaches]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:People from Akron, New York]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n